      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, I see! You are absolutely right to be confused; I certainly didn't mean to make you feel like you were dealing with a goblin in the bathroom. I apologize for the confusion.\n\nHere are the actual steps to change the washer on a compression faucet:\n\n1.  **Turn off the water supply**: Locate the shut-off valve under the sink and turn it clockwise to stop the water flow.\n2.  **Remove the cap**: Unscrew the cap from the faucet handle.\n3.  **Loosen the nut**: Use a wrench to loosen the compression nut that holds the old rubber washer in place.\n4.  **Remove the old washer**: Pull the old rubber washer off the spout.\n5.  **Install the new washer**: Place a new rubber washer onto the spout.\n6.  **Tighten the nut**: Screw the compression nut back on by hand, then use the wrench to tighten it firmly until it is snug.\n7.  **Turn the water back on**: Open the shut-off valve and test the faucet to ensure it is no longer dripping.\n\nLet me know if you need clarification on any of these steps!",
