    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to check further; a dripping faucet is often a sign that the goblin inside the valve has been replaced but is still hungry for food. If the washer is new but the water keeps running, it's likely a **clogged aerator** (the little mesh screen at the tip of the spout) or a **worn-out cartridge** inside the valve body.\n\nTo fix this, you need to remove the cap, unscrew the entire faucet body (which might require a wrench), and then inspect the tiny mesh screen at the very bottom of the spout. If that screen is clogged with debris, you'll need a small brush or a toothpick to clean it out. If the screen is clean but the water still drips, the internal valve mechanism itself is likely worn out and needs replacement.\n\nSo, while the washer is the goblin's favorite snack, the aerator is the goblin's favorite hiding spot, and the valve is the goblin's favorite workplace. Make sure to check the aerator first, as it's the quickest fix!",
